05133nam a2200685Ia 9780791483718DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20062006nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97807914837187 a10.1515/97807914837182doi  a(DE-B1597)681340  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBR163b.W66 2005 7aREL0330002bisacsh04a274/.05/08222200aWomen's Space :bPatronage, Place, and Gender in the Medieval Church /ced. by Sarah Stanbury, Virginia Chieffo Raguin. 1aAlbany : bSUNY Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (271 p.) :bTotal Illustrations: 0  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSUNY series in Medieval Studies00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tIntroduction -- tSigns of the Body: Gender, Sexuality, and Space in York and the York Cycle -- tEly’s St. ÆThelthryth: The shrine’s Enclosure of the Female Body as Symbol for the Inviolability of Monastic Space -- tMargery Kempe and the Arts of Self-Patronage -- tReal and Imaged Bodies in Architectural Space: The Setting for Margery Kempe’s Book -- tThe Seat Under Our Lady: Gender and Seating in Late Medieval English Parish Churches -- tAccess to Salvation: The Place (And Space) of Women Patrons in Fourteenth-Century Florence -- tGender, Celibacy, and Proscriptions of Sacred Space: Symbol and Practice -- tMen on the Right—Women on the Left: (A)Symmetrical Spaces and Gendered Places -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis interdisciplinary collection addresses the location of women and their bequests within the single most important public and social space in pre-Reformation Europe: the Roman Catholic Church. This innovative focus brings attention to gender and space as experienced in the medieval parish as well as in monastic and cathedral space. Through provocative handling of historical content and theory, the contributors explore strategies of exclusion and of inclusion and note patterns of later writers who neglect or rewrite records of female presence.Essays on the York religious cycle, the chronicle of the monastery at Ely, and The Book of Margery Kempe explore how medieval writers used texts as fictive spaces on which to graft responses to the gendered uses of real church buildings. These text-based essays are juxtaposed with tightly focused archival research in art history and history on Florentine patronage and English parish seating, as well as with more broadly synthetic studies on access of women to shrines and on gendered left-right placement in ritual art.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aChristian womenxReligious lifexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aChurch historyyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 0aWomen in ChristianityxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aWomenxReligious life. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Art. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 4aHistory : History. 4aHistory : Medieval Studies. 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh1 aBlanton, Virginia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrench, Katherine L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeller, Ena Giurescu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRaguin, Virginia Chieffo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRaguin, Virginia Chieffo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchleif, Corine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchulenburg, Jane Tibbetts, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStanbury, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aS